</CENTER></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/udragoon412.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Dragoon412</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(1/8/02 10:55:49 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovefrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=252.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Damage calculations</span><hr size=1> I'm usually not much of a number cruncher in terms of gameplay, but as my friends ceaselessly point out, I tend to be more interested in the game mechanics than the game itself. <br>
<br>
The other caveat is that playing a defensive tanking pally means that I can take an unreal amount of punishment and create such an ungodly amount of aggro that cleric group heals aren't even likely to get the mob off me, all the while contributing to the group's general well-being with my healing chant. The only issue I have is keeping aggro from other tanks (keeping in mind, this is all read... I'm not terribly experienced with the class yet) - namely halberd-wileding, style-happy armsmen... short term, mind you -- mobs seem to have an intense hatred for that regen chant.  ;)  I want to know what type of weapon is going to be most effective at generating enough of a taunt to keep the mob on me ALL the time, without having to ask the casters to hold off nuking or the other tanks to not use so many styles.<br>
<br>
So that's why I want to know damage formulae (or aggro formulae... those would be great, too) -- not so I can run around being a permanant mini-maxed, cookie-cutter character, but simply because I don't understand how damage works now -- unfortunately common-sensical rules don't apply to fantasy settings, and I hate the idea of sitting there being far less effective than I -could- be because I'm ignorant. I just look at it this way: spec levels indicate my physical skill with a weapon, but not the knowledge of how to use that weapon most effectively; that I've gotta learn myself.<br>
<br>
So, I'm not going to be carrying around 20 weapons all the time so I can adapt to every fathomable situation in the most effective way possible; I've committed to piercers and I'm sticking with them -- I like the way they &quot;feel.&quot; I just want to know what role delay plays in the overall dealing of damage and therefore, mob aggro. <p>--For every winner, there are dozens of losers. Odds are you're one of 'em. 
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ugallatin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Gallatin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(1/9/02 9:11:42 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovefrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=252.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://astro.temple.edu/~fmoffat/img/kitty6.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Damage calculations</span><hr size=1> Drag, I think it's kinda cool to be interested in the game mechanics, to figure out how it works...just doesn't appeal to me, hehe. I do benefit from what people who investigate those things find out, though :-)<br>
<br>
It's funny, I like games so much that I've thought about trying to get into making games instead of sys admin'ing for a living...but I have a feeling that turning what I love into my job would kill the love, you know? Especially since I find myself so uninterested in the actual mechanics of the game, hehe. <p><b>Gallatin</b><p>
